{#- LANE — where the close stops → reading-column prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="qbyec-lane" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Where the close stops</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:16px;">We close the books. Your CPA files the taxes.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>The year-end close is <strong>bookkeeping and management accounting</strong>: reconciliations, adjusting entries, account cleanup, 1099 information returns, and a locked, CPA-ready file. It is <strong>not</strong> tax preparation. TechBrot does <strong>not file income taxes, set tax positions, or represent you before the IRS</strong> &mdash; that is your CPA or EA&rsquo;s lane. We book adjustments per their year-end guidance, or hand off a clean file for them to finalize, and we coordinate the handoff so nothing falls through the cracks. Keeping that line bright is what keeps the work honest.</p>
      <p>The 1099 piece sits inside the bookkeeping lane: where scoped, we prepare and file the 1099-NEC/1099-MISC <strong>information returns</strong> for your contractors as a bookkeeping service &mdash; verifying W-9s, TINs, and payment totals &mdash; while any <strong>tax determination</strong> (worker classification calls, deductibility) is deferred to your CPA. Payroll <a href="/quickbooks/payroll/year-end/?intent=accounting">W-2 and 1099-from-payroll forms</a> are generated from QuickBooks Payroll and handled on that page; contractor 1099-NEC is the part that folds into this close.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

{#- FOUNDATION — annual close built on monthly → reading-column prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qbyec-foundation">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">The annual close, built on the monthly one</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:16px;">Twelve clean months make a short December.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A year-end close is far smaller when the books were closed every month along the way. The annual close is built on the <a href="/accounting/month-end-close/?intent=accounting">monthly close</a> &mdash; if each period was reconciled and locked as it ended, December is a final reconciliation, a handful of year-end adjustments, 1099s, and the closing-date lock, not a year-long reconstruction. Where the books were never closed, the first move is catching the periods up and reconciling them before the annual lock; we scope that together on the discovery call.</p>
      <p>If you&rsquo;d rather work it yourself, the free <a href="/resources/checklists/year-end-checklist/">year-end checklist</a> is the self-serve companion to this engagement. And when the question is &ldquo;are the books even ready to close?&rdquo;, that diagnosis is the <a href="/accounting/year-end-review/?intent=accounting">year-end review</a> &mdash; many clients run the review first and bring the close in to fix and lock what it flags.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

